\section{Introduction}

Recent LLM agent systems increasingly adopt heterogeneous model configurations, or \emph{agent teams}~\cite{TODO}, where multiple models assume distinct cognitive roles within a single workflow.
Humans do not think equally hard about every step of a task: figuring out \emph{what} to do requires careful reasoning, but carrying out each step is often routine~\cite{kahneman}.
Agent teams apply the same idea: one model decides the approach, another carries out the steps.
This works because a detailed plan compensates for the executor's limited reasoning~\cite{vygotsky}, which is also reflected in our results: a 9B-parameter model achieves only 60\% accuracy under homogeneous plan-execute, but reaches 88\% when a 27B model plans for it.
Examples in production include Claude Code's \texttt{opusplan} mode, OpenAI Codex, and open-source frameworks (OpenCode, Aider, Cursor) with configurable multi-model pipelines.
Anthropic reports 11.9\% cost reduction per agentic task using such configurations~\cite{anthropic_advisor}; our best heterogeneous team achieves the highest accuracy at 8$\times$ lower cost than the best homogeneous baseline (Section~\ref{sec:results}).

Why not just use a single model?
Tool selection accuracy degrades sharply as the number of available tools grows~\cite{berkeley_bfcl}, and recent work on large-scale tool-use environments confirms a fundamental misalignment between planning and execution abilities within a single model~\cite{toolgym2025}.
Our experiments confirm both effects: single agents either refuse to act or thrash without progress on 38\% of tasks, while plan-execute teams resolve the majority of these failures by separating tool selection (planning) from tool invocation (execution).

Configuring agent teams is difficult due to three structural properties that have no analogue in single-model evaluation.
We illustrate with plan-execute, the most widely deployed architecture, though these properties generalize to other multi-role configurations.
%
\textbf{(i) Cross-role dependency.} The output of one role directly shapes the behavior of downstream roles. In plan-execute, plan quality affects the executor's turn count, token consumption, accuracy, and latency. Cost, accuracy, and system performance are therefore coupled across roles and cannot be evaluated or optimized independently.
%
\textbf{(ii) Role asymmetry.} The planner (one call, reasoning-heavy) and executor (many calls, tool-use-heavy) require fundamentally different model capabilities. A model's strength in one role does not predict its strength in the other.
%
\textbf{(iii) Task-dependent role sensitivity.} Which role is the bottleneck changes per domain: some task domains are executor-critical (swapping executors shifts accuracy by up to 45 points), others are planner-critical (swapping planners shifts accuracy by 30 points while executor choice barely matters). Without knowing which, practitioners cannot make informed model assignments.

Despite these properties, no existing evaluation framework addresses them.
%
\textbf{(i)} Benchmarks such as MAESTRO~\cite{ma2026maestro} and HAL~\cite{kapoor2025hal} support heterogeneous model configurations, but focus on evaluating agent frameworks, not on how team composition interacts with cost and performance. None systematically vary role-model assignments to expose the coupling described above.
%
\textbf{(ii)} Existing cost tracking reports total cost per run, but does not decompose cost by role or model the dependency between plan quality and execution cost.
%
\textbf{(iii)} No method exists to determine, for a given task domain, whether upgrading the planner or the executor yields a larger gain.

To address these gaps, this paper introduces AgentCAP, a benchmark for evaluating heterogeneous LLM agent teams.
Our contributions are:

\mypar{AgentCAP, the first benchmark that evaluates agent teams by systematically varying role-model assignments}
We evaluate all pairwise planner-executor combinations across 5 API models and 5 self-hosted models on 3 domain-stratified benchmarks (open-domain tool-use, medicine, finance), with single-agent baselines for direct comparison.
Every model serves as both planner and executor, directly exposing the cross-role dependencies that single-model benchmarks miss.

\mypar{A role-decomposed cost model that captures cross-role dependency}
We decompose per-task cost into plan cost and execution cost, modeling how plan quality affects executor turn count and token consumption.
This unifies API per-token pricing with self-hosted GPU amortization and enables per-role cost-accuracy tradeoff analysis.

\mypar{A swap-sensitivity method for measuring domain-dependent role criticality}
We measure accuracy changes when swapping models between roles, classifying task domains as planner-critical or executor-critical without human annotation.
This tells practitioners exactly where to invest model budget for a given task domain.
